\begin_layout Section
Literature Review: The Elite and Their Relationships
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How to understand the elite and their relationships behind the facade of
 formal institutions has been one enduring question in social science.
 For instance, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

power elite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 thesis emerged in 1950s stimulated a heated debate on whether power in
 America was concentrated on a small cohesive group of quasi-hereditary
 and well-positioned elites 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hunter1953,Mills2000,Dahl1961"

\end_inset

.
 The debate in turn has significantly advanced our understanding about the
 nature of democracy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Dahl1971"

\end_inset

.
 In studies of authoritarian politics, scholars have been increasingly confronte
d by the same problem, particularly after the recent development in studies
 of authoritarian institutions.
 Although recent theoretical works like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Svolik2012"

\end_inset

 provide us valuable insights to link authoritarian institutions with elite
 contention and cooperation, we still lack a systematic framework to conceptuali
ze and analyze the actual power-sharing dynamics in authoritarian regimes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our lack of a systematic framework has much to do with the highly secretive
 nature of authoritarian politics.
 It restricts researchers to employing methods such as Hunter's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Hunter1953"

\end_inset

 sociometric interviews emerged in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

power elite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 debate.
 Many studies of authoritarian elites therefore have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

been based on anecdotal and impressionistic `readings of the tea leaves'
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 137"
key "Ishiyama2014"

